            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this disability insurance calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool helps you understand how much of your income would be
                replaced if you became unable to work due to illness or injury,
                and whether you may want additional disability insurance.
              </p>

              <h3>Key steps</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimate your target income replacement.</strong> Many
                  planners suggest replacing
                  <strong>60–70% of gross income</strong> to stay close to your
                  current lifestyle while disabled.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add up existing benefits.</strong> That includes
                  employer short-term or long-term disability, government
                  benefits (like SSDI or state disability), and any other
                  reliable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compare target vs. benefits.</strong> The difference
                  is your <strong>coverage gap</strong>—the amount of private
                  disability insurance you might want to consider.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Factor in savings.</strong> Your emergency fund can
                  help you get through the elimination period and cover any
                  remaining gap.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Formulas used</h2>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>1. Target monthly income</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( I_{\text{annual}} \) = gross annual income</li>
                  <li>\( r \) = target replacement rate (e.g. 0.65 for 65%)</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Monthly income: \[ I_{\text{monthly}} =
                  \frac{I_{\text{annual}}}{12} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Target monthly income: \[ I_{\text{target}} =
                  I_{\text{monthly}} \times r \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>2. Estimated monthly benefits</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \( r_{\text{employer}} \) = employer disability percentage
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \( B_{\text{gov}} \) = government disability benefit per
                    month
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \( B_{\text{other}} \) = other reliable monthly income
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Employer benefit: \[ B_{\text{employer}} = I_{\text{monthly}}
                  \times r_{\text{employer}} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Total monthly benefits: \[ B_{\text{total}} =
                  B_{\text{employer}} + B_{\text{gov}} + B_{\text{other}} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>3. Coverage gap & replacement percentage</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Coverage gap (recommended additional disability benefit): \[
                  \text{Gap} = \max\left(0,\; I_{\text{target}} -
                  B_{\text{total}}\right) \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Income replacement percentage: \[ \text{Replacement \%} =
                  \frac{B_{\text{total}}}{I_{\text{monthly}}} \times 100 \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>4. Savings runway</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( S \) = liquid savings</li>
                  <li>\( E \) = essential monthly expenses</li>
                  <li>\( B_{\text{total}} \) = total monthly benefits</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  Before benefits (during elimination period), we assume you
                  must cover the full expense: \[ \text{Runway}_{\text{before}}
                  = \frac{S}{E} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  After benefits start, the remaining monthly shortfall is: \[
                  \text{Shortfall} = \max\left(0,\; E - B_{\text{total}}\right)
                  \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  If shortfall &gt; 0: \[ \text{Runway}_{\text{after}} =
                  \frac{S}{\text{Shortfall}} \] otherwise, savings are not
                  needed to cover ongoing expenses.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Short-term vs. long-term disability insurance</h2>
              <p>
                Disability insurance comes in several forms. Understanding the
                differences helps you interpret your results:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Short-term disability (STD)</strong> – Often provided
                  by employers. Benefits may start after a short waiting period
                  (7–14 days) and last <strong>up to 3–6 months</strong>.
                  Replacement rates can be relatively high (e.g., 60–80% of
                  income).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Long-term disability (LTD)</strong> – Designed for
                  serious, longer-lasting disabilities. Benefits usually start
                  after an <strong>elimination period</strong> (often 90–180
                  days) and can last for several years or until retirement age.
                  Replacement rates are often <strong>40–70% of income</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Government programs</strong> – In the U.S., Social
                  Security Disability Insurance (SSDI) and Supplemental Security
                  Income (SSI) provide benefits if you meet strict medical and
                  work-history criteria. Many workers also have access to
                  <strong>state disability programs</strong> (for example, in
                  New York, New Jersey, California, and a few other states).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to read your results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Coverage gap ≈ $0</strong> – Your existing benefits
                  and other income already meet your target replacement rate.
                  You may still want to review details like benefit period,
                  definition of disability, and cost-of-living adjustments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Moderate gap</strong> – You may want to explore
                  <strong>individual long-term disability insurance</strong> to
                  close the gap, or adjust your target replacement rate if your
                  budget is tight.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Large gap</strong> – Consider a combination of:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Increasing disability coverage, if affordable</li>
                    <li>Building a larger emergency fund</li>
                    <li>
                      Reducing fixed expenses (housing, debt, subscriptions)
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This calculator is
                  <strong>for education and planning only</strong>. It is not a
                  quote, policy offer, or guarantee of benefits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Actual disability insurance benefits depend on policy terms,
                  underwriting, waiting periods, offsets, and exclusions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Government benefits like SSDI have strict eligibility rules
                  and may be denied or delayed.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For personalized advice, consult a licensed insurance
                  professional or fiduciary financial planner.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>
                Is disability insurance worth it if I already have savings?
              </h3>
              <p>
                An emergency fund is essential, but a long-term disability can
                last for years. Even a large savings balance can be depleted
                quickly if you are replacing most of your income from savings
                alone. Disability insurance is designed to protect your income
                so that your savings can remain focused on long-term goals like
                retirement.
              </p>

              <h3>What “definition of disability” should I look for?</h3>
              <p>
                Policies vary. Some use an
                <strong>“own occupation”</strong> definition (you are disabled
                if you cannot perform the duties of your current job), while
                others use an <strong>“any occupation”</strong> definition (you
                are disabled only if you cannot work in any reasonable job).
                Own-occupation coverage is usually more protective but can be
                more expensive.
              </p>

              <h3>How do taxes affect disability benefits?</h3>
              <p>
                In many cases,
                <strong>employer-paid disability benefits are taxable</strong>,
                while benefits from a policy you pay for with after-tax dollars
                may be tax-free. This calculator works in gross (pre-tax) terms
                for simplicity. For a more precise plan, consider the after-tax
                value of your benefits.
              </p>

              <h3>Where can I learn more about disability programs?</h3>
              <p>
                For U.S. federal programs, see the Social Security
                Administration’s resources on disability benefits. Many states
                also publish detailed guides on temporary disability and paid
                family leave programs. Always rely on official government and
                insurer documentation for eligibility and benefit rules.
              </p>
